A1,A9,A10,A12 are binary basis min/max values, rest are continuous For target variable mean is ~45% ==> variable is not imbalanced

  1. Distribution of Data
my_plots <- lapply(names(org_cc_data), function(var_x){
  p <- 
    ggplot(org_cc_data) +
    aes_string(var_x)

  if(var_x %in% list("A1","A9","A10","A12","R1")) {
    p <- p + geom_bar()

  } else {
    p <- p + geom_density()
  } 

})

plot_grid(plotlist = my_plots)

#class(summary(org_cc_data))

A15 seems highly skewed towards right side and A11 seems slightly skewed

  1. Correlation Heat Map
cormat <- round(cor(org_cc_data),2)
cormat[upper.tri(cormat)] <- NA
melted_cormat <- melt(cormat)
# plotting the correlation heatmap
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = melted_cormat, aes(x=Var1, y=Var2,
                                   fill=value)) +
geom_tile() +
geom_text(aes(Var1, Var2, label = value),
          color = "white", size = 3)

If |cor| >0.3 ==> Significant (Let) R1: A8,A9,A10,A11 A11: A8,A9,A10 A10: A9 A9: A8 A8: A2
